She moved to a blank page and wrote the date on it. Below it, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"You're rereading memories?" asked Ivory, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, which otherwise consisted only of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had spoken up about her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had also changed. She had been given tasks that condemned her to loneliness, as punishment for her difference.
Iel also had to stay in service of the princess, but it wasn't too bad, because it gave her a friend.
"C'est bientôt ton anniversaire, je crois ?", demanda Ivory, se rappelant que l'anniversaire de la princesse tombait dans quelques jours. Kari hocha la tête, un éclat triste dans ses yeux bleu pâle.
"Tu veux le fêter ?" Tout en posant la question, iel se souvint de ce qu'elle lui avait répondu la dernière fois.
Non, botta Kari en touche. Ivory savait que c'était un sujet difficile pour elle. C'était le jour où elle avait été confinée dans sa chambre et que sa mère avait été bannie. Ivory était encore bébé quand c'était arrivé, mais iel se souvint de l'indignation des serviteurs et des habitants. Iel avait entendu dire que la reine Eirwen était une bonne reine, mais qu'elle avait aussi cette faculté étrange de prédire l'avenir.
"Bon... qu'as-tu envie de faire ?", demanda-t-iel. Kari leva les yeux avec enthousiasme. Elle tendit un papier à Ivory. Mais quand iel y jeta un œil...
Toile de peinture 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Palette
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" said Ivory, turning to the silent princess who was typing furiously, shaking her braids back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess getting excited about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and not found in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" offered Ivory, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and plunged back into her memories, wrapping herself again in her thick blanket.
Iel stepped out of the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't within her realm, like paint.
Iel turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the maids.
"I've heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I've heard she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered her ears, because trying to ignore them didn't work. Iel headed toward the royal painter's room, which was in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as elaborate as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered in the room, easels covering every last centimeter of the wall. Surprisingly, Iel saw none of this. The room was clean and there was a red velvet background with a stool just in front. On the stool, stood Prince Aquilo, who was being painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! You're here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" asked Aquilo, giving Ivory a wink.
"Pardon, petit prince", répondit-iel en l'ignorant partiellement, pour chercher les objets que sa silencieuse amie souhaitait. "Je suis là juste pour récupérer des fournitures".
"Ah, la fillette va repartir très vite ?", demanda Aquilo, "Mais je voulais te voir !"
"Eh bien, pas moi". Ivory avait trouvé les fournitures d'art de sa liste et les avait placées dans une caisse qu'iel avait dénichée. "Et je ne suis pas une fille."
Le prince n'y avait pas pensé toutefois. "Oh ma chérie, tu sais bien que c'est juste une phase ! Ça te passera quand tu auras grandi !", marmonna-t-il.
"Je dois y aller", dit-iel, soudain mal à l'aise, à cause des paroles du prince, qui lui rappelaient tout le mal que les gens disaient au sujet de son identité de genre. Je veux vraiment m'éloigner de lui.
"Are you leaving already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the painter's complaints.
"That is not the behavior of a future king!", scolded Ivory.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to live." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What do you say to a date?" Ivory shivered. Of course, she had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone an heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word 'no' means?", shouted Ivory, pushing the prince out of her way.
"Oh no," replied Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want a date with me instead of others? You must have a hundred suitors?"
He interrupted, still smiling all the time: "500, to be exact." He threw his hair back, making it fly in the cold air.
"So why me instead of another? I'm the threat to the palace." Iel wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
